{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_kent_ver01/data/sn92051227/00415620755/1920112201/0080.xml":{"full_text":"THE TIMES: MONDAY, NOVEMBER 22, 1920\n\"SEVEN\n11 rr\nV\nThe store closes daily at 6 o'clock\nTORTURED BY\nHER JTOIflACH\nAfter Ten Years, She Found\nRelief In \"Fruit-a-tives\"\n8307 Sacto Ave., Sacbames-to, Cal.\n\"I had Stomach Trouble for tea years,\nlrhich became so bad that I got\nStomach Cramps two or three times\na week.\nAfter years of terrible torture, I\nread about Fruit-a-tives' or Fruit\nLiver Tablets, and sent for a trial box.\nAfter taking- the trial box, I felt\nbetter, so kept on taking 'Fmit-a-tives?\nfor nearly a year, and am thankful to\nsay Fruit-a-tives' saved my life\".\nIKS. F. ST STOLZ.\n50c. a box, 6 for $3.50, trial size 25e,\nAt dealers or from FRCIT-A-TIVE3\nYOUNG CAPTAIN\nFACED MUTINY\nB Francisco. Nov. 19. Twelve\nHuii-gvr-crazea seamen iacea za-year-\noid captain E C. Genereaux on the\ndeck of hie schooner. Rose Mahoney,\nas the ship slid and rocked in the\nseas of a heavy gale off the California\ncoast.\nAfter nearly seventy days at sea a\nraging gale caught the flve-master,\nstripped it of its sails and nearly\nsent it to the bottom. The food sup\nply was gone, the pangs of hunger\nwere on the men. Cptain Genereaux,\nthe youngest clipper-ship captain ol\nan American vessel, had orders to\ngo to San Francisco. When the\ntorm abated the ship was off San\nPedro, several 'hundred miles down\nthe coast. Captain Genereaux gave\norders to \"tack\" and make for the\nhome port farther away. It was then\nthat the crew attempted to take\nthings into their own hands. They\ndeserted their posts and demanded\nthat the vessel put in to San Pedro\nOrders were orders to the young cap\ntain and he told the crew that they\nmust make for San Francisco.\nLike a flash the sparks of discon\ntent and strife rose in a flame of mu\ntiny. The men tried to take com\nmand. Captain Genereaux, young in\nyears, but stern in experience, faced\ntha mutineers.\n\"I. am master of this ship,\" he told\nthem. \"If I decide to tack off shore\nthat will bo the course followed.\nhould I decide to run across to China\nthat also will be followed.\" With that\nhe drew two revolvers. The men re\nturned to quarters. Several days lat\ner another ship was sighted and food\nwas secured for the men of the Rose\nMahoney. She arrived in San Fran\ncisco safely.\nSETTLES LAW CASK\nBY FLIPPING COIN\n(By International News Service.)\nAkron, Ohio, Nov. 19. By flipping\na penny Common Pleas Judge W. J.\nAhern broke a deadlock in connec\ntion with the settlement of a law\nsuit.\nAttorneys in the case declared th\ncourt's unusual procedure was a just\none.\nIt was a damage suit. The claim\nwas for $160. Judge Ahern advised\nthe plaintiff and defendant to settle.\nAlthough the defendant agreed to pay\n$50, the plaintiff held out for $60.\nWhen he found neither side would\nbudge. Jutfge Ahern Informed the liti\ngants of his plan for disposing of the\ncontroversy. Plaintiff and defendant\nagreed.\nTaking a cent out of his pocket,\nJudge Ahern said:\n\"Heads, you (the defendant) pay\n$60, and tails you (the plaintiff) take\n155.\"\nThe flipped cain fell upon a table\nheads up.\nThe defendant paid $60 and the\ncourt marked the case settled.\nMRST MAN TO WEAR HIS HAT\nIN COURT.\n(Ry International News Service.)\nSan Francisco, Now 19. For the\nfirst .time in history a man has\nbroken all precedent and worn his\nbat during court in a local court\nroom. The mnn'.was A. Singh, Hindu wit\nness. Singh came into the court\nroom wilh the customary turban on\nhis bean. The bailiff ordered the\nHindu to remove the covering. Ter\nror-p:rickrn. the Hindu started to\nflee 'the courtroom. 9\n\"It's against his religion to re\nmove his turban,\" his attorney ex\nplained to the court. Singh was call\ned bnfl: and pat- through the, trial\nwkh his turban m its ordained plE.ce.\nAUCTION\nSALE\nOf Interest to all those about to\nbuy various household articles\nllko\nFurniture, Bedsteads,\nDining Room Suites,\nLiving Room Suites,\nBed Room Suites,\nSpring, Mattresses,\nStoves, Chairs, Tables,\nEtc., Etc.\nAlso a flue allotment of\n50 Silk Floss Mattresses\nat Less Than $15.00\nAH sizes.\nAUCTION SALE ON\nTUESDAY,\nNOVEMBER 23, 1920,\n10 A. M. to 12 M.; 1 I. M. to 4\nI SI. at\n271 MIDDLE STREET\nA. DeLemos,\nAUCTIONEER\n100 Lee Ave.\nSilverware\nA great number of the popular patterns in table\nsilver have received xjut prices, and prominent among\nthese is the\n\"Lufbery\" Pattern\nThis is a Colonial design with bright finish which\nwas made during the last three'or four years and\nreceived the name of Connecticut's aviator who lost\nhis life in France. It is a heavy plated ware without\nornamentation, and will last for a great many years..\nAll sold in sets of six\nRegular Now.\nMedium Knives, hollow handles, $11.29 $10.00\nMedium Knives, modeled handles, 4.62 4.00\nDessert Knives, modeled handles, 4.52 $3.90\nFruit Knives, 3.94 3.25\nMedium Forks, $6.04 5.00\nDessert Forks, 5.36 4.75\nSalad Forks, $6.04 $5.00\nTable Spoons, 6.04 5.00\nSoup Spoons, 6.04 5.00\nDessert Spoons,. 5.36 5.10\nBouillon Spoons, $5.78 $5.00\nOrange Spoons, 3.94 3.25\nTeaSpoons, 2.99 2.50\nCoffee Spoons, 2.99 2.50\nButter Spreaders, 5.36 4.75\nSpecials in Dinnerware\nfor Thanksgiving\nAmerican Porcelain\n100 piece set with gold\nand white. Regularly\n$28.00\nFor $25.00\nAmerican Porcelain\n50 pieces with design\nin medallion effect.\nRegularly $16.00\nFor $14.00\nAmerican Porcelain\nGold and white border,\n112 pieces. Was $23.00\nFor $19.00\nAmerican Porcelain\n112 piece set\nBlue flowers and pink\nroses, green foliage.\nVery quaint and pleas\ning. A pattern of which\none will not tire. Was\n$60.00\nFor $53.00\nAmerican Porcelain'\n100 piece set with\nbluebird decoration,blue\nline and gold edge. Was\n$34.00\n\"For $30.00\nMain floor.\nOKDDVReaaco\nAbout this time before Thanksgiving\nIt is well to replenish your china cabinets\nMany of the choice patterns are Special for this week\nList of reductions follows\nKlever Kraft Pieces\nAttractive and convenient Ramekins,\nCustard Cups and other articles which have either\nPyrex or Guernsey ware in s ilver plated frames\nCustard Cups, $1.42 $1.05 each\n$1.16 90 cts each\nRamekins, 85 cts 65 cts each\n90 cts 75 cts each\n$1.10 85 cts each\nSauce Dishes, v; S $1.73 $1.35 each\nCovered Casseroles, individual style,\nwere $1.47 and $1.68 $1.10 and $1.30 each\"\n'Sherbets, were $2.00 now $1.15 each\nSome Distinctive Hats\nA few which are quite unusual and irresistible\nMushroom Hat with short brim, lightly puffed\ncrown of pearl gray duvetyn. The brim is covered\nwith quilled blue taffeta ribbon with a gold edge.\nShortbrimmed Sailor of sapphire blue velvet with\ntwo fancy drooping heckle feathers.\nBrimmed Hat composed entirely of reseda green\nvelvet ribbon, braided crown, shirred brim with sin\ngle spray of hand made pink silk rose. The brim faced\nwith sapphire blue. Exceedingly simple and very at\ntractive. Picture Hat with moderately wide roll brim. Hat\ncovered with black and silver brocade, facing of brown\nKolinsky fur on the brim. A novel ornament of brown\nostrich.\nHat of Taupe Duvetyn, roll brim faced with mole\nskin fur to which is applied garlands of French flowers\nin old rose, gold and blue.\nTurban having crown of silver and blue brocade.\nBrim faced with superb quality of Siberian squirrel.\nTwo handsome plumes of blue and gray ostrich at\none side.\nTarn model with wide, full crown of silver and\ngold brocade on which are appliqued flowers and\nleaves of moleskin held in place by small glittering\nsequins.' Very French.\nSecond floor.\nIf It Is An Umbrella\nMucn style is\nshown in umbrellas.\nIf one does not exact\nly long for rainy\nweather, still she will\nbe quite willing to\ncarry one of these\nstunning affairs to\nward off rain. Not\nonly the sticks but the\ncolored silks are\ntempting.\nFrench Ivory,\nBraided or Twisted Leather and plain handles project\nthemselves through the frames and terminate in stunt\ned short ends, carved or plain.\nRings for carrying are in jade, lapis, ivory or\namber. The leather thong through which the wrist\nslips is an approved fashion.\nOne very elegant model has a stick and end of\nimitation carnelian elaborately carved.\nCoverings are of silk, gloria or cotton.\nPrices from $2.50 to $18.00 and up.\nFor men, \"Prince of Wales\" handles, or plain\nmannish styles trimmed with sterling silver.\n$2.75 to $18.00\nIt will be wise to make early selections while the\nstock is complete and interesting.\nMain floor, front.\nQ)c D D) Read CO\n4\nSome Reductions on Baby Carriages\nCaused by the fact that the stock is too heavy for\nthis thne of year. By taVng advantage of this sale\nat a greatly\none may secure a valuable\nlowered price.\nPerambulators in light colors, cream and oyster\nwhite. These are perfectly constructed to the smallest\ndetail. Regular price $65.00\n$50.00 to close out\nCarriage of finely wo-en material, frosted blue, a\nmost attractive shade, with wide deeply tufted\ncushions. Regular price $65.i00\nFor $52.00\nA Flat Weave Carriage very wc-\" built, corduroy\nlining and cushions. Regularly $50.00\nAt $40.00'\nGray Carriages, lined with grav.\n$44.00\nRegularly\nOyster White\ncorduroy lining.\nFor $35.00\nCarriage, enamel finished with\nThis is $48.00\nIn addition twenty different patterns at like\nreductions. We consider this an important offering.\nFor The Little Girl\nBedroom Set of white ivory, bed, dresser,\nchiffonier, rocker and chair. This set, which is very\nwell built and finished with white ivory, has for\ndecoration on the head of the bed and on the fronts of\nthe drawers of the dresser and chiffonier, quaint\nDutch figures, little girls and boys of the playmate age\ntrotting about in their wooden shoes and strange little\ncaps, most interesing to look at. This set is really\nlarge enough for a grown person of moderate size.\nThe chairs are strong enough to accommodate anyone.\nThe dresser and chiffonier are of a very useful size.\nPriced at $165.00\nt Fourth floor.\nCarving Sets\nA large assortment in\nmany sizes and styles.\nBird, game and the large\nsizes for roasts. The\nblades are mounted in\nstag and white ivory\nhandles with silver and\nnickel ferrules. Best\nAmerican steel.\nPairs and three-piece\nsets.\n$3.00 to $15.00\nBasement.\nSift the Ashes\nin a rotary sifter that\nfits over ash can or bar\nrel and that' is practical\nly dustless. It is made\nof heavy galvanized\nsheet steel. .Very easy\nto operate.\n$5.00\nWood Box Shaker\nSifters that fit a barrel\nor can.\n$2.00\nBasement.\nPictures\nNew and attractive\nColored Prints\nfor the\nHolidays\nThird floor.\nA Truck\nto move the ash cans.\nThis is very necessary\nand can be used for tak\ning the ashes from the\ncellar to the walk. It\nhas wheels for flat roll\ning and is also con\nstructed for drawing up\na flight of stairs.\n$5.00\nFull line of Ash Cans\nfrom\n$3.00 up.\nBasement.\nOk D D) Read co\nWHY BUSINESS\nLOOKS BETTER\n(Bl International News Service.)\nWellesley, Mass., Nov. 19-Ton rea\nsons why the business outlook in the\nUnited States is favorable and why\nbusiness men should assume a more\noptimistic attitude are given by\nRoger W. Babson, famous statisti\ncian. Here they are:\n\"First, the working people in this\ncountry are in possession of the great\nmajority of the bonds issued by the\nUnited States government during the\nwar. This is a very favorable sign,\nfor it shows that the great mass of\npeople are in a sound financial condi\ntion. \"Second, that as a result of the\ncoming of national prohibition two\nand one-half billion dollars pre\nviously wasted in this industry yearly\nis now available for business projects\nthat are more useful and mon likely\nto promate the welfare of all people.\n\"Third, that in spite of the wide\nsprea opinion to the contrary, the\nFederal Reserve Banking System has\nbeen an important factor in stabiliz\ning financial conditions in this coun\ntry.\n'Fourth, that advertising is now\nan influential means of moulam\npublic opinion. This prffession has\nnow reached such an advanced and\nscientific stage in its development\nthat it is a logical means by which\nthe people of the country can be con\nvinced that, contrary to their present\nopinion, business is really on a firm\nlasis and that there is no cause for\nthe nrownt linnrpjinn.\n\"Fifth, that the argument that the\nfailling off of our foreign trade will\nprove ruinous is ill-founcted, for such\ntrado only constitutes o per cent, of\nthe total. What little stoppage there\ncan.be in this field, therefore, is of\nlittle or no consequence and will have\nno noticeable effect on the general\nbusiness outlook.\n\"Sixth,' that recently the. standard\nization of manufacturing processes\nhas been increasing with such amaz\ning rapidity that there has been a\nconsiderable reduction in the cost of\ncommodities. This is a permanent\ninfluence of no mean importance and\nshould not be slighted in any consid\neration of the future of industries in\ngeneral.\n\"Seventh, that all statistics gath\nered recently offer overwhelming\nproof that seasonal nuctuations an\nproduction in this country are rapidly\ndecreasing. This will prove to be\nvery beneficial, as It will tend to\nmake the demands for labor more\nconstant.\n\"Eighth, that taxation will be rad\nically reduced in the near future.\n\"inth, that rapid progress 4s being\nmade in industrial education with\nthe result that the men employed In\nindustrial plants are much better\ntrained for their tasks and are per\nforminar them with far greater effi\nciency. The trade schools that are\nnow established in all sections of the\ncountry are accomplishing wonders\nin this wav.\n\"Tenth, that the United States as\na result of the war is now a creditor\nnation instead of a debtor nation,\nand therefore, is in a very powerful\nposition in the business world.'\nENRICO CARUSO BUYS\nDIAMONDS IN DENVER\nDenver, Nov. 19 One more step\ntoward replenishing the valuable col\nlection of jewelry stolen from his\nLong Island home was taken by\nErico Caruso, Italian tenor, when he\nsauntered into a Denver jewelry store\nand purchased gems to the reputed\nvalue of $6,000. k\nAmong the stones bought by Ca\nruso, according to the local dealer,\nwas a diamond from an .original set\nowned by -the Czar Nicholas of Rus\nsia. The Denver jeweller announced\nthat the diamond from the Czar's col\nlection came into his possession\nthrough purchase from a Dallas,\nTex., merchant.\nCaruso, it was said, displayed keen\nknowledge of the value of diamonds.\nJAPANESE CAPTURE\nMEXICAN TRADE\nMexico City, Mexico, Nov. 19.\nJapan has captured the Mexican trade\nin electric light butfbs. The Japanese\nare offering the bulbs at prices about\n20 per cent lower than the prices of\nAmerican firms.\nThe Japanese are also taking pos\nsession of other important fields. They\nare f tig ;crockery a,t prices about\n25 cent lower than the prices of\nAmerican exporters.\nThe Swiss have control of the Mex,\nlean trade in watches. An American\nhaving broken nis watch recently,\ntried to iuy an \"Ingersoll.\" He could\nnot find the American watch, but was\noffered Swiss substitutes in nearly all\nof the stores. t,\nEATS 21 DOl'GHTNCTS\n(By International News Service.)\nBoston, Nov. 19. William J. An\nderson, 27 years old, a former in\nmate of the State Hospital at Bangor,\nMe., arrested in Union Square,- Som\nkerville by Patrolmen I-Cillourhy and\nCharry on the charge of vagrancy,\ntold the officers that he was so fam\nished from his two-day trip in a\nfreight car- that he could eat two\ndozen doughnuts. When the officers\nproduced the \"sinkers\" Anderson dis\nposed of twenty-one.\nIn the Somerville court he was\nfound\" guilty of the vagrancy charge\nand was sent to Bridgewater\nESSENCE OP LUCK.\nBucyrus. Nov. 1 9. -\"Cappy\" Haala,\nservice man with the E. F., and lo\ncal butcher, set a steel trap under his\nbutcher shop to catch rats. Next\nmorning, he pulled out the trap to\nrind he had caught a good-sized\nhealthy skunk. \"Cappy\" shed his\nworking clohtes in the barn.\nAUTOISTS SEEK BETTER\nHIGHWAYS IN\nOHIO\n(By International News Service.)\nColumbus,. Nov. 19. The Ohio\nGood Roada Federation will urge the\nstate (legislature next winter to pro-\nj vide legislation remedying the fol\nj lowing \"principal evils\" in Ohio high\nways: \"Unimproved sections frequent,\niv without maintenance. In main\nmarket roads; long, unsatisfactory\nand\" improperly marked detours; vil\nlage sections of important roads be\ning unimproved for lack, of funds;\ndeath-tray grade crossing in the\ncountry, and an unadequate guide\npost system.\"\nFederation members a'.so will urge\nbe permitted when eaoinu nununnu\nthat reconstruction of city streets\nbe permitted when two-thirds of abut,\nting property owners petition council\nto do so and that entire cost of such\nrecomsructlon, except for intersec\ntions, be charged to the property\nowners.\nIt is claimed many city streets are\nin bad condition and that, in view\nof the fact that municipalities haven't\nsufficient money to meet their share\nof the cost of making such improve\nments, residents along such streets\nare willing to pay all the cost.\nbody of a new-born infant is water\nand 5 to 65 per cent of the body of\nan adult.\nDRINK MORE WATER AND\nKEPP HEALTHY\n30,000-POUND CANNON FOR SALE\n(By International News Service.)\nBoston, Nov. 16. Would you like\nto get a cheap -30. 000-pound gum\nfor your small son to play with?\nNineteem Civil war cannon, ranging\nfrom fifteen to sixteen inches ond\nweighing from 30,000 to 50,000\npounds, are going begging at Bangor,\nMe.\nThe ordnance department has tried\nin vain to sell them, and has finally\ntaken to offering them to cities and\ntowns. Thus far there have been noth\ning but rejections, with thanks.\nThe guns are located at Fort Knox,\nnot far from Bangor. There has\nnever been a shot fired \"in anger\"\nfrom any of them.\n(By International News Service.)\nBoston, Nov. 19. Drink more\nwater and keep well is old advice,\n-but it cannot be improved upon, is\nthe comment of a Boston physician.\nDr. Fritz B. Talbot, who has made\nspecial investigations tn-.o the value\nand importance of water in the hu\nman system.\n\"The purpose of water is to keep\n.he maintains. .The various elements\nfor life will then be in solution to\ncarry food from one part of the body\nto th eother and to carry from the\nbody waste products and abnormal\nelements.\nThe human body is composed large\nly of water;- 63. to 71 per cent of the\n11 El.\nSHEASBY In this city, Sunday, Nov.\n21, 1SS0, Mary A., wife of Herbert\nSheasby. i.\nFriends are invited, to -attend t\"C\nfuneral from her late residence, 406\nPeauonnock street, on Tuesday, Nov.\n23 \"at 8:30 a. m., and from St. Augus\ntine's church, where a solemn high\nmafs of requiem wi!l be offered for\nthe repose of her soul at 9 o'clock.\nBurial in St. Michael's cemetery, a\nTODAY'S WANTS\n1W) liAlE FOR CLASSIFICATION.\nBUNvlALOW, 71 Barnum Terraca; new\nfive room, modern; fine lot; improve\nments; vacant; easy terms. Lamson,\n2879 Fairfield Ave. H22sto","height":"26476","width":"21592"}}
